primaryData.textualContent: In terms of threats to the bank, which are potentially achievable by high NPL ratio, it is relevant to mention here the case of Italian banks. According to pessimistic observers, many Italian banks may not continue to have enough capital to operate normally. The weakest banks desperately need to raise capital, but the issue is that it is extremely hard to find investors. The bigger lenders have committed to underwriting new share issues for their weaker rivals but they, in turn, also have needed external support. The government has obliged the banks to set up a fund called Atlas that will act as a backstop for banks that are trying to raise capital but cannot find buyers for their new issues of shares. If there is any money left over, the fund will invest in the banks non-performing loans. However, that fund does not have enough firepower. Significant securitizations of NPLs have failed to materialize and Italy s loan problem is currently, barely improving. The overall stock of bad loans for 15 Italian banks fell in 2016 for the first time in the past eight years, according to DBRS, the Canadian rating agency, which analysed the lenders results. Yet the proportion of so-called sufferance the worst class of bad loans, where banks are exposed to insolvent borrowers had risen slightly. According to the IMF, while the Italian economy grew 0.9 percent last year, its fastest pace since 2010, it will not return to pre-crisis levels for another decade.
